Technological determinism is a term for a wide range of ideas in practice: from technology offering or technological obligation to a strict sense that human fate is driven by an underlying logic linked to scientific laws and their appearance in technology.
Most interpretations of technological determinism have these two general concepts: the development of technology follows a path that extends for the most part beyond cultural or political influence, and that technology in turn has 'effects’ on societies that are inherent rather than socially conditioned.
For example, some will say that the arrival of the car automatically leads to the construction of roads.
However, a national road network is not economically feasible for just a few cars and new production methods are being developed to reduce the cost of car ownership.
The massive car ownership also causes a greater number of accidents on the road and this leads to the development of new techniques in the field of health care in order to restore the human body.
